    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-12-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="130"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d130">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> papers,
                        <persName>Whitman</persName> file</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1" type="from"
                            >Churchill</persName> to President <persName
                            corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1" type="to">Eisenhower</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mid-Ocean Club, Bermuda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-12-07">7 December
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>We agreed, did we not, that Admiral <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                        >Strauss</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1">Lord
                        Cherwell</persName> should compile a White Paper of the documents, and their
                    linking together, which constitute the story of Anglo-American relations about
                    the Atomic Bomb. You and I will then consider and discuss whether it will be
                    helpful or not to publish. Personally I think it will be. We both desire a
                    fuller interchange of intelligence<note n="1" xml:id="d130fn1">On the morning of
                        Dec. 7, <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName> had handed
                        to <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> a memorandum
                        by <persName corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1">Lord Cherwell</persName> expressing
                        the British desire to extend the interchange of intelligence regarding
                        Soviet nuclear tests. The memorandum, which is attached to the source text,
                        is not printed.</note> and the fact that secrecy is evaporating through
                    growth of knowledge between us, and alas between both of us and Soviet Russia,
                    makes it desirable that we two should make the best joint progress we can. Your
                    speech will, I think, encourage the new atmosphere. <persName
                        corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1">Cherwell</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1">Strauss</persName>, I understand, take it that they
                    should prepare the White Paper.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">W.C.</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
